 To calculate the probability that both Phil and Sarah get the same number, we need to consider each possible outcome and its probability. Since the probabilities of landing on each number are given, we can calculate the probability of both getting the same number for each case and then sum these probabilities.
</think> <answer>
\begin{align*}
P(\text{same number}) &= P(\text{both get 1}) + P(\text{both get 2}) + P(\text{both get 3}) + P(\text{both get 4}) \\
&= \left(\frac{1}{10}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{2}{10}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{3}{10}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{4}{10}\right)^2 \\
&= \frac{1}{100} + \frac{4}{100} + \frac{9}{100} + \frac{16}{100} \\
&= \frac{30}{100} \\
&= \frac{3}{10}
\end{align*}
